olfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</span></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Base.html">base</a> 2 method o=
f counting in which only the digits 0 and 1 are used. In this <a href=3D"ht=
tps://mathworld.wolfram.com/Base.html">base</a>, the number 1011 equals <im=
g src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline1.svg"=
 class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D=
"0" width=3D"236" height=3D"21" alt=3D"1=C2=B72^0+1=C2=B72^1+0=C2=B72^2+1=
=C2=B72^3=3D11">.
 This <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Base.html">base</a> is used =
in computers, since all numbers can be
 simply <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RepresentedAs.html">repres=
ented as</a> a string of electrically
 pulsed ons and offs. In computer parlance, one binary digit is called a <a=
 href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Bit.html">bit</a>,
 two digits are called a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Crumb.htm=
l">crumb</a>, four digits are called a
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Nibble.html">nibble</a>, and eigh=
t digits are called a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Byte.html">b=
yte</a>.
</p>
<p>
An integer <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binar=
y/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 may be represented in binary in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/lang=
uage/">Wolfram
 Language</a> using the command <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com=
/language/ref/BaseForm.html">BaseForm</a></tt>[<i>n</i>,
 2], and the first <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/Binary/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"d">
 digits of a real number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/Binary/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x">
 may be obtained in binary using <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.co=
m/language/ref/RealDigits.html">RealDigits</a></tt>[<i>x</i>,
 2, <i>d</i>]. Finally, a list of binary digits <img src=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula"=
 style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"5" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"l"> can be converted to a decimal rational number or integer=
 using
 <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/FromDigits.html">=
FromDigits</a></tt>[<i>l</i>,
 2].
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"538.9" src=3D"https=
