ign=3D"left">11101</td></tr><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"right">10</td><td a=
lign=3D"right">1010</td><td align=3D"left">20</td><td align=3D"right">10100=
</td><td align=3D"right">30</td><td align=3D"left">11110</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
A <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Negative.html">negative</a> numb=
er <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline=
6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bor=
der=3D"0" width=3D"21" height=3D"21" alt=3D"-n"> is most commonly represent=
ed in binary using the complement
 of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Positive.html">positive</a=
> number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/=
Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n-1">, so <img src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline8.svg" class=3D"in=
lineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D=
"135" height=3D"21" alt=3D"-11=3D00001011_2">
 would be written as the complement of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D=
"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"123" height=3D"21" a=
lt=3D"10=3D00001010_2">, or 11110101. This allows addition to be carried
 out with the usual carrying and the leftmost digit discarded, so <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline10.svg" cla=
ss=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" =
width=3D"85" height=3D"21" alt=3D"17-11=3D6"> gives
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Binary/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" styl=
e=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"111" height=3D"6=
9" alt=3D" 00010001   17=20
11110101__  -11__=20
00000110   6.  "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
The number of times <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equati=
ons/Binary/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"k">
 that a given binary number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/image=
s/equations/Binary/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"97" height=3D"22" alt=3D"b_n..=
.b_2b_1b_0">
 is divisible by 2 is given by the position of the first <img src=3D"https:=
//mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"4=
6" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b_k=3D1"> counting from the right. For example, <im=
g src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline14.svg=
" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"75" height=3D"21" alt=3D"12=3D1100"> is divisible by 2 twic=
e, and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/In=
line15.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%=
" border=3D"0" width=3D"75" height=3D"21" alt=3D"13=3D1101"> is divisible b=
y 2 zero times. The number of times that
 1, 2, ... are divisible by 2 are 0, 1, 0, 2, 0, 1, 0, 3, 0, 1, 0, 2, 0, 1,=
 0, 4,
 0, 1, 0, 2, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A007814">A007814</a>), wh=
ich is the
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BinaryCarrySequence.html">binary =
carry sequence</a>.
</p>
<p>
Real numbers can also be represented using binary notation by interpreting =
digits past the "decimal" point as negative powers of two, so the binary di=
gits
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline16=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"155" height=3D"22" alt=3D"...b_2b_1b_0.b_(-1)b_(-2)..."> =
would represent
 the number
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Binary/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" styl=
e=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"370" height=3D"2=
0" alt=3D" ...+b_2=C2=B72^2+b_1=C2=B72^1+b_0=C2=B72^0+b_(-1)=C2=B72^(-1)+b_=
(-2)=C2=B72^(-2)+.... "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
Therefore, 1/2 would be represented as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline17.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"30" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"0.1_2">, 1/4 as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/Binary/Inline18.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"0.01_2">,=
 3/4 as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/I=
nline19.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"0.11_2">, and so on. The =
sequence of binary digits for the integers
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline20=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D0">, 1, ... concatenated tog=
ether and
 interpreted as a binary constant give the binary <a href=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/ChampernowneConstant.html">Champernowne
 constant</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Bi=
nary/Inline21.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"148" height=3D"21" alt=3D"C=3D0.11011100..._=
2">
 (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A030190">A030190</a>).
</p>
<p>
Unfortunately, the storage of binary numbers in computers is not entirely s=
tandardized. Because computers store information in 8-<a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/Bit.html">bit</a> <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/Byte.html">bytes</a>
 (where a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Bit.html">bit</a> is a s=
ingle binary digit), depending on the
 "word size" of the machine, numbers requiring more than 8 <a href=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/Bit.html">bits</a>
 must be stored in multiple <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Byte.h=
tml">bytes</a>. The usual <tt>FORTRAN77</tt>
 integer size is 4 bytes long. However, a number <a href=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/RepresentedAs.html">represented
 as</a> (byte1 byte2 byte3 byte4) in a VAX would be read and interpreted as=
 (byte4
 byte3 byte2 byte1) on a Sun. The situation is even worse for <a href=3D"ht=
tps://mathworld.wolfram.com/Floating-PointArithmetic.html">floating-point</=
a>
 (real) numbers, which are represented in binary as a <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/Mantissa.html">mantissa</a>
 and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Characteristic.html">characte=
ristic</a>, and worse still for long (8-byte)
 reals!
</p>
<p>
Binary multiplication of single bit numbers (0 or 1) is equivalent to the <=
a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AND.html">AND</a> operation, as can=
 be seen in the following <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Multipli=
cationTable.html">multiplication
 table</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"table-responsive">
<table align=3D"center" class=3D"mathworldtable">
<tbody><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wo=
