le=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"2=
1" alt=3D"=C3=97"></td><td align=3D"left">0</td><td align=3D"center">1</td>=
</tr><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"center">0</td><td align=3D"left">0</td><td=
 align=3D"center">0</td></tr><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"center">1</td><td =
align=3D"left">0</td><td align=3D"center">1</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"570.6" src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/BinarySums_900.svg" class=3D"" alt=
=3D"BinarySums">
</div>
<p>
Consider the cumulative <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DigitSum.h=
tml">digit sum</a> of all binary numbers up to 1, 2, ..., <img src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Binary/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inl=
ineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"=
9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">.
 The first few terms are then 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 12, 13, 15, 17, 20, 22, ...=
 (OEIS
 <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A000788">A000788</a>). This sequence in monoton=
ic increasing
 (left figure), but if the main asymptotic term is removed, a sequence of h=
umped curves
 (right figure; Trott 2004, p.&nbsp;218) tending towards the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/BlancmangeFunction.html">blancmange
 function</a> is obtained.
</p>
